<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-10-10T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-10-10T02:00:00-05:00" n="378" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d378">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5151/959: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-10-10T14:00:00+07:00">October
                                    10, 1943—2 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received October 10—12:41 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1909. Secretary of the Treasury from Adler. In view of delays in
                            reciprocal aid negotiations,<note n="68" xml:id="d378fn68">See <ref target="#pg_515">pp. 515</ref> ff.</note> would it be worthwhile
                            for Treasury to consider arrangement on lines [of] arrangement already
                            in effect in Middle East to sell gold on free market in China in order
                            to cover U.S. Government expenditures in China, once Chinese Government
                            starts operating in market? Advantages are obvious, drawback is that
                            Chinese Government might be reluctant to agree. [Adler.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>